{
  "doc_id": "17363",
  "text": "Patients were asked to self-report their symptom burden immediately before and at 2 and 4 h after study drug administration by using the Vanderbilt Orthostatic Symptom Score [CITATION_1] . The patients were asked to rate the severity of nine symptoms on a scale of 0 to 10 (with 0 reflecting an absence of symptoms). The sum of the scores at each time point was used as a measure of symptom burden (lower score reflects reduced symptom burden). The nine symptoms were mental clouding, blurred vision, shortness of breath, rapid heartbeat, tremulousness, chest discomfort, headache, lightheadedness, and nausea. This symptom score has been used previously by our center [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . These symptoms were chosen because they reflect common complaints of patients with POTS.",
